LARDD 1
TITLE LardOS Releases
TEXT Every feature addition gets a release entry. The running kernel version is the active release.
TEXT Suffix policy: a=official, b=beta-experimental, p=hotpatch.
TEXT Hardware profiles extend releases by target: universal, seabios, ami, vbox, usb, realpc.
TEXT New or risky feature bundles should use b first; a is for promoted stable builds only.
TEXT Codenames append after the channel as OS-era subnames, for example v2.0.6b-mirage. LTS lines are retired.

SECTION v2.5.0b-mirage
ITEM Adds native LREC video wallpaper support through wallpaper lrec file.lrec and cfg wallpaper lrec file.lrec.
ITEM Reuses the existing user-owned LardOS screen recording format instead of adding an external codec or host-video dependency.
ITEM Scales grayscale LREC frames across the desktop as live wallpaper while wallpaper.lardd stores MODE lrec and FILE visibly for user editing.
ITEM Extends wallpaper status, rollback restore, config reload, and POST/selftest coverage to the LREC path.
ITEM Preserves color, grid, stripes, checker, BMP wallpaper, screenrec, screenshots, PinClip/MegaClipboard, RXE/SYSRXE, LFS/LAR, and user-control values without feature loss.
ITEM Ships as beta because this adds a live-rendering wallpaper mode.

SECTION v2.4.1b-mirage
ITEM Adds pinclip from fixed-slot [megaclip-slot] so useful MegaClipboard history can be frozen into stable PinClip shortcuts.
ITEM Adds megaclip pinfrom/fixfrom/keep/remember fixed-slot [megaclip-slot] aliases for the same user flow.
ITEM Omitting the source slot pins the latest MegaClipboard item; providing 1..9/0 pins that visible history slot.
ITEM Adds PINHEX fixed-slot persistence so file/blob clips copied from MegaClipboard keep exact bytes across reloads instead of being flattened to text.
ITEM megaclip clear still clears moving history only; fixed slots remain editable, creatable, reloadable, writable, and deletable through PinClip commands.
ITEM Preserves PinClip fixed-slot persistence, MegaClipboard history modes, GUI shortcuts, LardOS Connect, RXE/SYSRXE, LFS/LAR, and user-control values without feature loss.
ITEM Ships as beta because this extends the new clipboard shortcut workflow.

SECTION v2.4.0b-mirage
ITEM Adds PinClip fixed clipboard shortcuts on top of MegaClipboard, with ten user-owned slots that do not move when normal clipboard history changes.
ITEM Adds pinclip/fixedclip/pclip commands for list, set, pull, write, clear, reload, and selftest.
ITEM Adds megaclip pin, pinpull, pinwrite, unpin, pins, and pinreload subcommands for users who want one clipboard command surface.
ITEM Adds GUI shortcut routing: Ctrl+Space then 1..9/0 still pulls MegaClipboard history, while Ctrl+Space then P then 1..9/0 pulls fixed slots.
ITEM Stores fixed slot lines visibly in writable megaclip.lardd, and pinclip reload lets user edits become live OS behavior.
ITEM Preserves MegaClipboard history modes, app icons, LDI assets, RXE/SYSRXE, GUI, LardOS Connect, LardSec, LFS/LAR, and user-control values without feature loss.
ITEM Ships as beta because this extends keyboard-shortcut clipboard behavior and editable clipboard persistence.

SECTION v2.3.0b-mirage
ITEM Extends LDI with an editable LDI2 text image format that mixes vector commands with palette bitmap rows.
ITEM Adds RXE/SYSRXE ICONASSET file.ldi support so apps can own real image icons while old ICON text fallbacks still work.
ITEM Ships native LDI icon assets for bundled desktop, dock, RXE, SYSRXE, folder, and office-style apps.
ITEM Keeps window corners and resize handles in the dynamic GUI renderer because they are core size/hit-test UI, not replaceable fixed artwork.
ITEM Preserves RXE/SYSRXE, APPKIT, window resizing, dock/desktop, glyphs, LGUILIB, wallpaper, LAR/LFS, and LardOS user-control values without feature loss.
ITEM Ships as beta because this adds a new native image asset surface.

SECTION v2.2.1b-mirage
ITEM Tightens LAR method 1 so the stored salt is public metadata only and no longer mixes in a password hash.
ITEM Adds selftest checks that the password text is not stored in the archive, that same-file archives with different passwords keep the same public salt, and that their ciphertext differs.
ITEM Keeps existing password-protected LAR extraction commands and method 0 archives compatible.
ITEM Documents that LAR stores LP1 metadata, public salt, payload CRC, length, and ciphertext, not the password or a password-derived stored verifier.
ITEM Ships as beta because it corrects the new archive-protection metadata surface.

SECTION v2.2.0b-mirage
ITEM Changes the built-in LFS volume to LFS v2, a record-stream format with unbounded varuint file counts, offsets, sizes, and extent chains.
ITEM Keeps legacy LFS v1 readable so existing built-in/LFS seed files do not disappear.
ITEM Adds LFS parser support for metadata numbers larger than the current mounted image window without converting them into fixed u32/u64 disk ceilings.
ITEM Adds lfsdoctor layout and POST selftest coverage for the v2 unbounded-varuint structure, including a huge out-of-window extent entry.
ITEM Documents that runtime hardware and mounted memory are finite, but the LFS disk format no longer bakes in a petabyte/exabyte-style structural maximum.
ITEM Ships as beta because this changes the native filesystem layout while preserving existing user-visible files.

SECTION v2.1.0b-mirage
ITEM Adds extract archive.lar member password as a first-class shell alias for password-protected LAR extraction.
ITEM Strengthens the LAR POST/selftest so protected archives fail if the original plaintext payload still appears in the archive bytes.
ITEM Documents that LAR method 1 is an actual keyed-stream payload lock, not a metadata-only password marker.
ITEM Keeps lar extract, larx, larpass, existing method 0 archives, and method 1 protected archives compatible with v2.0.9b.
ITEM Ships as beta because it tightens the new archive protection path and command surface.

SECTION v2.0.9b-mirage
ITEM Adds password-protected .lar members through native LAR method 1 while preserving existing method 0 stored archives.
ITEM Adds lar pass out.lar member sourcefile password / larpass to create a single-member password-protected archive in a writable user file.
ITEM Extends lar extract / larx so protected members require the user-supplied password and reject wrong passwords before writing lar_extract.txt.
ITEM lar list and GUI LAR listing now show password-protected members without exposing their contents.
ITEM Adds an in-tree keyed stream, salt, and CRC check with no external compression or crypto library dependency.
ITEM Adds POST coverage, LUNIT command checks, README/architecture/LSH docs, LARS control-room examples, and userlaw native-format wording.
ITEM Preserves old bundle.lar, larls, larx, LARSH, RXE/SYSRXE, KMO, MediaFS, screen capture, Mirage naming, and user-control values without feature loss.
ITEM Ships as beta because this adds a new archive protection method and shell write path.

SECTION v2.0.8b-mirage
ITEM Codifies the visible version-number contract: v<large-cycle>.<feature-or-change>.<patch-or-code-change><channel>-<subname>.
ITEM The third number is one digit only, 0 through 9; when it would pass 9, the carry moves into the feature/change number even for a small code edit.
ITEM release policy now prints the triplet/carry rule inside LardOS so users do not have to remember it from outside notes.
ITEM POST now checks the active kernel version against the one-digit patch/carry rule so malformed future versions are caught visibly.
ITEM Updates README, architecture notes, LSH docs, userlaw.lardd seed text, and the LARS control room note.
ITEM Preserves Mirage subname policy, a/b/p channel policy, hardware-profile releases, screen capture, GUI, RXE/SYSRXE, KMO, MediaFS, LiveUpdate, LardOS Connect, and user-control values without feature loss.
ITEM Ships as beta because this changes release-policy plumbing and POST validation.

SECTION v2.0.7b-mirage
ITEM Adds user-owned screen capture: screenshot writes compact LSHOT RGB565 snapshots to screen.lshot or a chosen writable file.
ITEM Adds screen recording: screenrec start/frame/stop writes compact LREC luma frames to screenrec.lrec without external video libraries.
ITEM Adds screencap.lardd status/report output, help/docs entries, POST writable-file checks, and a GUI capture selftest.
ITEM The GUI exposes a small capture API after final cursor/backbuffer rendering, so captures reflect the visible screen rather than a hand-built fake view.
ITEM Keeps capture files local, inspectable, overwriteable, and user-owned; no hidden upload, no host bridge, and no third-party codec dependency.
ITEM Preserves Mirage codename policy, AuxKernel REAL16, seed/default ownership, RXE/SYSRXE apps, KMO, LiveUpdate, MediaFS, GUI, LardOS Connect, and user-control values without feature loss.
ITEM Ships as beta because screen recording is a new GUI/file-system surface and should mature before promotion.

SECTION v2.0.6b-mirage
ITEM Retires the LardOS LTS release model; Tiara support is ended and there is no active LTS line.
ITEM Changes Tiara/Mirage style names into OS-era subnames instead of long-term-support promises.
ITEM Sets Mirage as the current subname and exposes it through generated version metadata, ver/status, release policy, release codename, codename.lardd, and userlaw.lardd.
ITEM Keeps release lts and lts.lardd as visible compatibility surfaces that explain the LTS retirement instead of hiding the policy change.
ITEM Keeps a/b/p suffixes and hardware release profiles unchanged; codenames append after the channel, such as v2.0.6b-mirage.
ITEM Preserves PanicRoom, AuxKernel REAL16, seed/default ownership, RXE/SYSRXE apps, KMO, LiveUpdate, MediaFS, GUI, LardOS Connect, and user-control values without feature loss.
ITEM Ships as beta because it changes release-support policy language and version metadata.

SECTION v2.0.5b
ITEM Corrects AuxKernel from the mistaken REAL8 beta wording to a REAL16 emergency profile.
ITEM auxkernel real16 now runs the primary BIOS 16-bit real-mode first responder probe and returns to long64.
ITEM Keeps auxkernel real8 as a visible compatibility alias that explains the correction and redirects to REAL16 instead of silently breaking old input.
ITEM Renames AuxKernel status, auxkernel.lardd report fields, global status, POST labels, and documentation to real16 bridge readiness, probe counts, last result, and marker bytes.
ITEM Updates the CPU bridge marker to a visible 0xA1/0x16 REAL16 probe signature.
ITEM Preserves PanicRoom, lockdown, keydrop, seed/default ownership, RXE/SYSRXE apps, KMO, LiveUpdate, MediaFS, GUI, LardOS Connect, and then-current Tiara LTS policy without feature loss.
ITEM Ships as beta because it corrects the emergency kernel mode contract introduced in v2.0.4b.

SECTION v2.0.4b
ITEM Pins AuxKernel to a REAL8 profile: an 8-bit byte-discipline first responder executed inside BIOS real mode.
ITEM Adds a CPU mode bridge request for auxkernel real8 so LardOS can prove the emergency path reaches real mode and returns to long64.
ITEM AuxKernel status, auxkernel.lardd reports, and global status now expose real8 bridge readiness, probe counts, last result, and marker bytes.
ITEM auxkernel real8 runs the explicit REAL8 probe; PanicRoom, lockdown, keydrop, and POST/selftest also touch the visible REAL8 path.
ITEM Keeps the safety line intact: no hidden hardware-damage path, no KMO dependency, and user-confirmed containment through lock/sync/key discard.
ITEM Preserves the v2.0.3b seed/default ownership model, RXE/SYSRXE apps, KMO, LiveUpdate, MediaFS, GUI, LardOS Connect, and then-current Tiara LTS policy without feature loss.
ITEM Ships as beta because it deepens the emergency kernel mode contract.

SECTION v2.0.3b
ITEM Replaces true read-only built-in behavior with user-overridable seed/default file behavior.
ITEM fs_open now checks user-owned writable overlays before built-in/LFS seed defaults, so the user's file wins.
ITEM DIR and merged storage listing now hide duplicate seed/default names when a user overlay exists.
ITEM write, append, copy, GUI saves, LiveUpdate, and KMO editing can create user-owned overlays for seed/default names instead of refusing control.
ITEM DEL -F, TOMB, RESTORE, and BLEED wording now describes seed/default removal records rather than immutable files.
ITEM Preserves bundled apps, RXE/SYSRXE, KMO, LiveUpdate, MediaFS, installer, security, GUI, LardOS Connect, and then-current Tiara LTS policy without feature loss.
ITEM Ships as beta because it changes filesystem ownership semantics while following the LardOS user-control value.

SECTION v2.0.2b
ITEM Adds apps/bundled/ as the dedicated source space for default apps that ship with LardOS.
ITEM Moves hello.sysrxe, demo_game.rxe, langdemo.rxe, lardwrite.rxe, lardsheet.rxe, and lardshow.rxe source out of kernel/fs.c.
ITEM Adds Makefile bin2inc rules that generate kernel app payload includes from apps/bundled during the build.
ITEM Keeps fs.c responsible for seed/default file registration only; bundled app behavior now lives in app files.
ITEM Preserves all bundled apps, office commands, RXE/SYSRXE loading, GUI registration, and writable office data files without feature loss.
ITEM Ships as beta because it changes source layout and build plumbing.

SECTION v2.0.1b
ITEM Deepens the bundled office apps while keeping them file-defined RXE programs.
ITEM LardWrite adds title, section, bullet, quote, code, find, and stats commands for richer LARDD documents.
ITEM LardSheet adds column editing, cell records, visible formula records, CSV-style export, search, sum, and average summaries.
ITEM LardShow adds deck title/theme editing, speaker notes, play mode, next/prev, and slide-number navigation.
ITEM Updates the RXE APPKIT surfaces so one Run input can execute plain text or office subcommands.
ITEM Keeps office_doc.lardd, office_sheet.lsheet, and office_deck.lshow user-owned writable files.
ITEM Preserves the Tiara active LTS support line and all existing RXE/SYSRXE, GUI, driver, connect, security, recovery, and raw-control surfaces.
ITEM Ships as beta because it expands a new default app family.

SECTION v2.0.0b
ITEM Adds bundled native office-style RXE apps: LardWrite, LardSheet, and LardShow.
ITEM Adds lardwrite.rxe, lardsheet.rxe, and lardshow.rxe as file-defined normal RXE apps rather than hand-coded GUI branches.
ITEM Adds writable user-owned office files: office_doc.lardd, office_sheet.lsheet, and office_deck.lshow.
ITEM Adds lword/lwrite, lsheet, and lshow shell commands for keyboard-first document, workbook, and deck workflows.
ITEM Adds office_guide.lardd, POST coverage, and LUNIT file/command checks for the bundled office surface.
ITEM Keeps Tiara as the active LTS support line while this build ships as beta; release lts now distinguishes current build codename from active LTS support codename.
ITEM Preserves RXE/SYSRXE file ownership, app extensibility, GUI, MegaClipboard, LardOS Connect, OSLink, LardSec, AuxKernel, WebStack, FSTWT, and user-control values without feature loss.
ITEM Ships as beta because it adds a new bundled app family and native office file surfaces.

SECTION v1.99.0a-tiara
ITEM Official LTS release named Tiara, promoting the v1.99 Connect raw-control compatibility track after build, media, POST policy, and boot-smoke checks.
ITEM Adds release lts and lts.lardd so the active LTS codename and one-LTS-at-a-time rule are visible inside LardOS.
ITEM Fixes release-channel parsing so future LTS names such as Mirage do not break a/b/p channel detection.
ITEM Keeps normal lconnect default-off, manual-grant, and non-input; deprecated lconnect input/quiet controls remain confirm-gated and logged.
ITEM Keeps OSLink, LardOS Connect normal mode, MegaClipboard, LardSec, AuxKernel, MediaFS, installer, WebStack, RenderFX, FSTWT, RXR/RXE/SYSRXE, KMO, SUM, software ECC, GUI, and branch-role separation intact.
ITEM Support policy: Tiara is the current LTS line; when Mirage ships as the next LTS, Tiara support ends because only one LTS may be active.
ITEM Ships as a because this is a stability/LTS promotion with no feature direction change and no feature loss.

SECTION v1.99.0b
ITEM Adds a Deprecated raw-control namespace for LardOS Connect edge cases.
ITEM Normal lconnect remains default-off, manual-grant, and non-input by default.
ITEM deprecated lconnect input on confirm unlocks keyboard/mouse/input resource names for user-chosen sharing, request, grant, and deny packets.
ITEM deprecated lconnect quiet on confirm enables promptless grants for resources the user already shared; it is deliberately not invisible because status and lconnect log show it.
ITEM Adds deprecated lconnect share/request/grant/deny forms with confirm gates, plus selftest coverage that normal lconnect still rejects input names unless the deprecated path is armed.
ITEM Keeps OSLink, LardOS Connect normal mode, MegaClipboard, LardSec, AuxKernel, MediaFS, installer, WebStack, RenderFX, FSTWT, RXR/RXE/SYSRXE, KMO, SUM, software ECC, and branch-role separation intact.
ITEM Ships as beta because input-resource and quiet-grant controls are raw-control compatibility paths and must mature before any stable promotion.

SECTION v1.98.0b
ITEM Adds LardOS Connect, a native LAN resource-sharing control plane for LardOS computers connected by cable/IP.
ITEM LardOS Connect can advertise and request MegaClipboard, CPU, GPU, storage, and peripheral resources while deliberately excluding keyboard and mouse input from sharing.
ITEM Adds lconnect/connect/lardconnect commands for status, on/off, direct manual IP, discover, peers, share, manual/auto grants, MegaClipboard sync, resource request/grant/deny, logs, poll, and selftest.
ITEM Default is off and manual-grant; the user must explicitly enable sharing and choose resources such as lconnect share all on.
ITEM Adds lconnect.lardd, POST coverage, status output, cfgsh control, netwatch/trace/journal events, and direct-cable IP setup for networks without DHCP.
ITEM Keeps OSLink, MegaClipboard, LardSec, AuxKernel, MediaFS, installer, WebStack, RenderFX, FSTWT, RXR/RXE/SYSRXE, KMO, SUM, software ECC, and branch-role separation intact.
ITEM Ships as beta because cross-machine hardware-resource sharing is broad and should mature visibly before promotion to a.

SECTION v1.97.0b
ITEM Adds MegaClipboard, a native keyboard-first clipboard system with ten typed slots for text, file bytes, labels, paths, and future OS objects.
ITEM Default mode is stack; megaclip mode single keeps one current slot, and megaclip mode order lists entries by copy order.
ITEM Adds GUI shortcuts: Ctrl+Y copies the active editor/response/selected item, Ctrl+P pastes latest, and Ctrl+Space then 1..9/0 pulls a chosen slot.
ITEM Adds megaclip/clip/mclip/clipboard commands for status, list, mode, push, file copy, pull, write, clear, and selftest.
ITEM Adds writable megaclip.lardd plus userlaw language for keyboard completeness: the OS should be usable by keyboard shortcuts without removing mouse control.
ITEM POST covers the slot/mode behavior and keeps LardSec, AuxKernel, MediaFS, installer, WebStack, RenderFX, FSTWT, RXR/RXE/SYSRXE, KMO, SUM, and software ECC intact.
ITEM Ships as beta because it adds a new cross-OS UI/data surface while preserving LardOS values: user-owned, visible, keyboard-complete, local, and reversible.

SECTION v1.96.0b
ITEM Adds LardSec software ECC placement controls for machines whose CPU or board does not expose hardware ECC.
ITEM Keeps secure ecc on/off as the master single-bit correction switch and adds secure ecc ram on/off plus secure ecc storage on/off.
ITEM Storage ECC remains on by default in native LSEC sealed headers; RAM ECC is explicit and keeps a volatile in-kernel ECC mirror for the latest sealed media image.
ITEM secure status now shows ecc, ram, storage, and ram_mirror state so the user can see where correction data lives.
ITEM POST selftest covers both storage-header ECC and RAM-only ECC correction without changing user-visible security counters.
ITEM Preserves LardSec keys, sealing, locking, AuxKernel, MediaFS, installer, WebStack, RenderFX, FSTWT, RXR/RXE/SYSRXE, KMO, SUM, raw-control gating, and delete/repair behavior intact.
ITEM Ships as beta because this adds a new software-ECC placement surface while keeping the LardOS value rule: visible, local, reversible, and user-owned control.

SECTION v1.95.0a
ITEM Adds AuxKernel, a tiny built-in emergency microkernel path for PanicRoom bridging, media lockdown, visible reports, and user-confirmed volatile key discard.
ITEM AuxKernel is compiled into the kernel and does not require KMO modules, KModTalk, app launchers, or the normal GUI to keep an emergency control path available.
ITEM Adds auxkernel/aux/emergency status, report, panicroom, lockdown confirm, keydrop confirm, and selftest commands; selfdestruct is a raw-control alias for keydrop confirm.
ITEM Integrates PanicRoom with AuxKernel entry counters and adds POST coverage plus writable auxkernel.lardd reports.
ITEM Keeps LardSec/LardLocker, MediaFS, installer, WebStack, RenderFX, FSTWT, RXR/RXE/SYSRXE, KMO, SUM, raw-control gating, and delete/repair behavior intact.
ITEM Does not implement fan, thermal, overheating, or hardware-damaging self-destruct paths; emergency containment uses visible lock, sync, audit, and key-discard operations only.
ITEM Ships as a because the implemented subset is defensive, explicit, local, inspectable, and matches the LardOS value rule that the user owns control without hidden damage.

SECTION v1.94.0a
ITEM Officially promotes the LardSec/LardLocker media sealing track after build, release media, and boot checks.
ITEM Keeps secure key, secure on/off, seal, lock, unlock KEY, ecc on/off, regen, scrub, and test from v1.94.0b.
ITEM Keeps default encrypted-at-rest MDFS media writes while preserving user choice through secure off and visible recovery keys.
ITEM Tightens the LardSec selftest so POST validates seal/ECC behavior without changing user-visible seal, ECC, or scrub counters.
ITEM Preserves MediaFS, installer, WebStack, RenderFX, FSTWT, RXR/RXE/SYSRXE, KMO, SUM, raw-control gating, and delete/repair features without feature loss.
ITEM Ships as a because the beta surface is stable and matches the LardOS value rule: security is visible, reversible, local, and user-owned.

SECTION v1.94.0b
ITEM Adds optional LardSec/LardLocker media sealing for user-owned at-rest protection.
ITEM secure key shows the visible recovery key; secure on/off, seal, lock, unlock KEY, ecc on/off, regen, scrub, and test are available from LSH and CFGSH.
ITEM MDFS media stores Y:/Z:/A: can be written as native LSEC sealed containers with stream encryption, scrubbed unused slack bytes, and block ECC records.
ITEM The ECC path can correct a single flipped bit per sealed block and refuses corrupted sealed media instead of silently trusting bad data.
ITEM The feature is on by default for at-rest media writes but remains reversible with secure off, and Magic treats secure/bitlocker as raw-control so accidental predicted execution requires magic -f.
ITEM Existing MediaFS, installer, WebStack, RenderFX, FSTWT, RXR/RXE/SYSRXE, KMO, SUM, and user-owned delete/repair controls remain intact.

SECTION v1.93.0b
ITEM Adds SPFX 1, a native subpixel display-defect filter script format for user-owned screen correction.
ITEM renderfx subpx can enable/disable, clear, manually add RECT/PIXEL rules, load displayfix.spfx, and selftest the filter path.
ITEM Each rule applies a region or single pixel with independent R/G/B subpixel percent multipliers so too-bright or too-dark screen defects can be corrected locally.
ITEM Adds writable displayfix.spfx so the user can edit and persist defect-correction scripts like other LardOS-owned settings.
ITEM POST and RenderFX selftests cover the parser and channel correction while preserving AA, brightness, ScreenRAM LSB, VBlank, resize modes, wallpaper, and WebStack behavior.
ITEM Ships as beta because this is a new display calibration surface; it adds control without removing any existing feature or changing LardOS values.

SECTION v1.92.1a
ITEM Officially promotes the v1.92 native WebStack line after the method expansion and HTTPS visibility hotpatch passed build, media, and boot checks.
ITEM Keeps HTTP/HTTPS GET, POST, HEAD, PUT, PATCH, DELETE, and OPTIONS from v1.92.0b intact.
ITEM Keeps webstack tls / webstack https, POST HTTPS TLS coverage, and webstack selftest from v1.92.1p intact.
ITEM Ships as a because this release changes no feature direction: it stabilizes the visible native WebStack without external browser or TLS libraries.
ITEM Preserves the LardOS value direction: user-owned method choice, visible encrypted transport diagnostics, native formats, and no feature loss.

SECTION v1.92.1p
ITEM Hotpatches the v1.92 WebStack line so HTTPS is visible and testable, not just an internal transport path.
ITEM Adds webstack tls / webstack https to show native LardTLS status, TLS 1.2 SNI, trust-anchor count, RSA limit, and supported cipher names.
ITEM POST now checks the HTTPS TLS surface beside the HTTP method builder, and webstack selftest covers both.
ITEM Keeps the seven-method HTTP/HTTPS builder from v1.92.0b intact: GET, POST, HEAD, PUT, PATCH, DELETE, and OPTIONS.
ITEM Preserves the LardOS value direction: native in-tree TLS, no external browser/TLS library, visible diagnostics, and no feature loss.

SECTION v1.92.0b
ITEM Expands the native internet stack with HTTP/HTTPS PUT, PATCH, DELETE, and OPTIONS beside the existing GET, POST, and HEAD.
ITEM The GUI Doc tab and CFGSH can cycle/select methods 1..7; POST, PUT, and PATCH accept URL|body while DELETE and OPTIONS stay bodyless.
ITEM NetWatch and LardTrace now record the selected generic method name instead of hard-coding only GET/POST/HEAD.
ITEM webstack methods documents the full native method surface, and POST/LUNIT coverage checks the extended request builder.
ITEM Ships as beta because this is a broad WebStack expansion, while preserving LARS, LARDD, NetWatch, TLS, GET/POST/HEAD, and user-owned method choice.

SECTION v1.91.1p
ITEM Hotpatches GUI window resize hit-testing so only the visible bottom-right resize grip starts a resize drag.
ITEM Left-top, right-top, and left-bottom corners no longer resize windows, preventing accidental reverse-corner resizing while moving or selecting windows.
ITEM Keeps stretch/live resize modes, app RESIZE fixed/reflow policy, fullscreen, wallpaper, dock, and desktop/window-manager behavior intact.
ITEM Preserves the LardOS value direction: no feature is removed, and user-owned window control stays explicit through the visible grip.

SECTION v1.91.0a
ITEM Officially promotes the user-owned desktop wallpaper feature after the beta build, release assets, and boot screenshots passed validation.
ITEM Keeps wallpaper color/pattern/BMP commands, writable wallpaper.lardd, cfg wallpaper, rollback, POST, LUNIT, and LiveUpdate wallpaper reload paths intact.
ITEM Preserves the previous grid desktop as the default, so existing GUI behavior remains compatible while users gain direct background control.
ITEM Ships as a because no feature direction changed: the release stabilizes the v1.91 wallpaper track and keeps LardOS user ownership values intact.

SECTION v1.91.0b
ITEM Adds user-owned desktop wallpaper settings to the default GUI.
ITEM wallpaper color 0xRRGGBB, wallpaper pattern grid/stripes/checker, and wallpaper bmp file.bmp apply immediately.
ITEM The active wallpaper is stored in writable wallpaper.lardd so the user can edit, sync, copy, or replace the config like any other OS-owned file.
ITEM cfg wallpaper, rollback snapshots, and LiveUpdate reloads understand wallpaper state.
ITEM Ships as beta because it adds a new GUI setting contract while preserving the previous grid background as the default.

SECTION v1.90.0b
ITEM Adds app-owned layout resize policy for RXE/SYSRXE and APPKIT apps.
ITEM Apps can declare RESIZE fixed, RESIZE freeze, or APPKIT RESIZE fixed to keep their UI layout from being recalculated when the user changes the window size.
ITEM Apps can declare LAYOUTSIZE width height, BASESIZE, or DESIGNSIZE to choose the fixed design canvas; APPKIT LAYOUTSIZE can change it at runtime.
ITEM RESIZE reflow remains the default and preserves the previous responsive behavior, so existing apps keep working without feature loss.
ITEM Ships as beta because it extends the app file/runtime UI contract while keeping user/app control intact.

SECTION v1.89.0a
ITEM Officially promotes the v1.88 GUI stability line after the hotpatch checks passed.
ITEM Includes stable stretch window resizing as the default while keeping renderfx resize live for users who want immediate reflow.
ITEM Keeps inactive-window saved-state rendering, APPKIT responsive label spacing, corner resize, fullscreen, RXE/SYSRXE apps, and user-owned render settings intact.
ITEM Ships as a because this release changes no feature direction: it stabilizes the tested hotpatch behavior and preserves LardOS user-control values.

SECTION v1.88.2p
ITEM Adds a stable stretch resize mode for windows: during corner drag, LardOS stretches/squashes the current window image and commits the real layout when the mouse is released.
ITEM renderfx resize stretch enables the stable mode, while renderfx resize live keeps the previous live reflow behavior available.
ITEM RenderFX status now reports the active resize mode so users can see which behavior is running.
ITEM This is a hotpatch for GUI stability and preserves the existing corner resize, fullscreen, RXE/SYSRXE, and APPKIT behavior.

SECTION v1.88.1p
ITEM Hotpatches the desktop window manager so inactive windows are drawn as real saved app windows instead of flat preview cards.
ITEM Adds corner resize handling for normal windows; users can drag the four corners while fullscreen remains a separate explicit mode.
ITEM Fixes APPKIT responsive layout label spacing so input/output/progress labels reserve vertical room instead of overlapping neighboring widgets.
ITEM Keeps custom RXE/SYSRXE UI freedom intact: responsive layouts avoid accidental overlap, while authored absolute layouts can still choose unusual placement.

SECTION v1.88.0b
ITEM Adds os/VERSION as the single source for the active release version.
ITEM Makefile reads VERSION for release names, hardware-profile artifact paths, and ISO volume IDs instead of carrying a second hard-coded version.
ITEM version.h now includes a generated version_gen.h, so kernel code uses the same VERSION source without editing version.h every release.
ITEM clean removes generated version_gen.h and .gitignore keeps it out of source control.
ITEM This removes repeat edits for normal version bumps while keeping RELEASES.lardd as the human release history.
ITEM Ships as beta because it changes build/version plumbing used by every release artifact.

SECTION v1.87.0b
ITEM Adds LiveUpdate, a runtime layer for changing files and file-owned code while LardOS is already running.
ITEM liveupdate file name text replaces a writable/user-owned file immediately; liveupdate apply/code also reloads the matching code registry.
ITEM .kmo changes reload KMO commands, .sysrxe and .rxe changes reload app registries and GUI launchers, .drfl reloads driver descriptors, .fstwts reloads filesystem translation, and .ltheme/.lguilib apply visual state.
ITEM Read-only built-in targets become user-owned overlays instead of blocking the user, keeping rollback/tombstone visibility and preserving the original built-in file path.
ITEM Adds liveupdate from source destination and liveupdate auto on/off plumbing for future automatic update flows.
ITEM Ships as beta because live runtime update is broad and should be exercised before official promotion.

SECTION v1.86.0b
ITEM Prepares the bootloader/staging path for future growth without removing features to fit.
ITEM Stage2 now writes boot metadata to bootinfo v2: kernel size, total sectors, high-memory copy address, loader chunk size, boot image sector count, persistent-store start, and kernel capacity.
ITEM Adds bootmeta so POST, status, bootmap, and bootreplay can show boot headroom and detect when the kernel is approaching the boot image limit.
ITEM Makes mkimg layout parameters configurable from Makefile variables, keeping the current compatible 1.44MB profile while making larger boot profiles a controlled build-time change.
ITEM Keeps the v1.79 high-memory copy path and all RXE/SYSRXE, GUI, filesystem, driver, and user-control features intact.
ITEM Ships as beta because it changes boot metadata and build-image layout plumbing that should be exercised across BIOS/VM profiles.

SECTION v1.85.0b
ITEM Adds APPKIT responsive/smart/flow/smartui/autofit layout for RXE and SYSRXE apps.
ITEM Responsive APPKIT keeps app-authored widget order, groups nearby rows, wraps controls instead of overlapping them, and lets OUTPUT/LIST fill remaining app space.
ITEM Updates bundled SYSRXE Hello, RXE Lang Demo, and RXE Maze to use responsive UI layout so their controls stay usable across window sizes.
ITEM Adds smarter desktop launcher placement that searches for a free grid spot and avoids the dock plus existing icons when adding bundled or user-created apps/folders.
ITEM Keeps RXE/SYSRXE file-owned app code intact; this is an app-library/layout upgrade, not an OS-owned hardcoded app rewrite.
ITEM Ships as beta because the new responsive layout engine should stabilize across more app designs before official promotion.

SECTION v1.84.1p
ITEM Hotpatches mouse movement latency by draining bounded PS/2 mouse batches before each GUI render.
ITEM Preserves every click, drag, wheel, and cursor Unicode path while avoiding one full redraw per mouse packet.
ITEM Fixes the v1.84.0b regression where heavier GUI/kernel work could make pointer motion feel slow or strange.
ITEM Ships as p because this is a focused usability regression hotpatch with no feature or value-policy change.

SECTION v1.84.0b
ITEM Adds crash, an explicit raw-control diagnostic command for OS inspection, PanicRoom testing, and fault-path verification.
ITEM crash status and crash dryrun mode show what will happen without crashing.
ITEM crash log records a diagnostic event without crashing; crash panic enters the normal PanicRoom/crashlog/capsule path.
ITEM crash ud2, div0, page, int3, and triple provide user-selected CPU exception/reset triggers for testing recovery behavior.
ITEM Ships as beta because it intentionally gives the user direct crash and fault triggers.

SECTION v1.83.1b
ITEM Extends bleed with an explicit overflow-style wipe option for stubborn broken files.
ITEM bleed overflow file performs a bounded in-slot overwrite pass on writable RAM files and media files before deletion, rather than an uncontrolled out-of-bounds memory corruption.
ITEM bleed dryrun overflow file shows the extra wipe routes without changing bytes.
ITEM Keeps the user-owned dangerous path visible, Magic raw-control gating intact, and all v1.83.0b delete routes available.
ITEM Ships as beta because this is deliberately destructive deletion behavior.

SECTION v1.83.0b
ITEM Adds bleed, a last-resort force-delete command for broken files.
ITEM bleed file visibly sweeps writable RAM, read-only hard-delete overlay records, and media stores instead of stopping at the first failed deletion path.
ITEM bleed dryrun file previews the routes it will try without changing bytes, so the dangerous path remains visible and user-owned.
ITEM The command is marked raw for Magic prediction safety; use magic -f bleed file only when you explicitly want automated execution.
ITEM Ships as beta because this is intentionally powerful deletion behavior and should be exercised before official promotion.

SECTION v1.82.0b
ITEM Extends FSTWT from a path translator into a filesystem coexistence layer with MODE TRANSLATE, MODE HYBRID, and MODE VM.
ITEM Adds MAIN and SUB declarations in .fstwts so scripts can choose the default filesystem namespace and mount coexisting VM-style sub filesystems such as sandbox:/path.
ITEM Adds fstwt fs and fstwt main name/reset so the user can inspect and choose declared main/sub filesystem views without editing shell code.
ITEM VM-style filesystems map explicit name:/path calls into isolated flat prefixes while MAP rules and old RXR/vpath fallbacks remain available.
ITEM Ships as beta because this changes the filesystem policy layer while preserving the user-owned FSTWT script surface and all existing fallback behavior.

SECTION v1.81.0b
ITEM Adds FSTWT, the File System Two Way Translator, as a live user-owned filesystem namespace layer.
ITEM .fstwts scripts use MAP external-prefix <=> lardos-prefix rules and translate both friendly paths to flat LardOS names and flat names back to friendly paths.
ITEM fstwt use file.fstwts can load scripts from main files, RAM files, media stores, the merged _ drive, RXR-style paths, or any file carrying an embedded FSTWTS block.
ITEM fs_resolve_os_path now checks FSTWT first, then keeps RXR aliases and existing virtual path flattening as fallback, so no prior path feature is removed.
ITEM Ships as beta because this is a broad filesystem translation surface that should be tested before official promotion.

SECTION v1.80.0b
ITEM Adds user-selectable RenderFX modes: no anti-aliasing by default, antianti edge recovery, basic anti-aliasing, and nonlinear edge-aware anti-aliasing.
ITEM Reworks brightness as multiplicative color-preserving post-blit scaling with the existing quality contrast control, rather than per-channel addition.
ITEM Adds ScreenRAM LSB storage mode so a selected rendered rectangle can carry scratch bytes in barely visible pixel least-significant bits.
ITEM Adds VBlank-style render sync mode that samples the VGA retrace flag for two-stage final blits and exposes hit/miss counters.
ITEM Ships as beta because this is a broad optional rendering feature bundle; defaults preserve the older sharp GUI path.

SECTION v1.79.1p
ITEM Hotpatches the SSAV generator so default .ssav files use the documented 16-byte header and frame data starts at 0x10.
ITEM Keeps the SSAV decoder, GUI screensaver renderer, and user-owned screensaver file format direction unchanged.

SECTION v1.79.0a
ITEM Official high-memory boot staging release: stage2 now reads through a 32-sector low bounce window and uses BIOS extended-memory block move to preserve the full LARDX/BOSX boot image at 0x01000000.
ITEM Expands stage2 to eight sectors and moves the kernel payload to LBA9, so the full kernel file no longer has to fit below VGA/EBDA.
ITEM Keeps bootinfo at 0x1000, stacks below staging, the installer preserved-image path, hardware IMG/ISO profiles, and all user-owned features without feature loss.

SECTION v1.78.0a
ITEM Official boot staging release: kernel low staging starts at 0x2000, bootinfo moves to 0x1000, and boot stacks move below staging.
ITEM Gives the in-tree kernel about 12 KiB more low staging room while keeping the v1.76.1p VirtualBox blank-screen safety rule.
ITEM Keeps _:, drive policy, RXR/RXE/SYSRXE, KMO, DRFL, installer, and hardware IMG/ISO releases without feature loss.

SECTION v1.77.0a
ITEM Official release promoting _:, the merged R:/X:/Y:/Z:/A: root, without feature loss.
ITEM Keeps dir _: listings, read-through commands, L-DOS mapping, visible R: write routing, and hardware IMG/ISO sets.

SECTION v1.77.0b
ITEM Beta track for _:, merged R:/X:/Y:/Z:/A: root with dir _:, read-through commands, and visible R: write routing.

SECTION v1.76.1p
ITEM Hotpatch release fixing the VirtualBox blank black screen seen after v1.76.0a boot.
ITEM Moves Stage2 from 0x7E00 to 0x0600, moves bootinfo to 0x4000, lowers the kernel staging buffer to 0x5000, and keeps real/protected-mode stacks below it so the larger kernel image does not cross into VGA/EBDA or overwrite its own boot stack.
ITEM Keeps the v1.76 OS virtual path namespace, RXR alias priority, MediaFS path mapping, quoted path words, vpath/pathmap, and all user-owned control behavior without feature loss.
ITEM Ships the full hardware-profiled IMG/ISO set for universal, seabios, ami, vbox, usb, and realpc.

SECTION v1.76.0a
ITEM Official release promoting the v1.76.0b OS virtual path namespace without feature loss or philosophy changes.
ITEM Keeps folder/inside/path resolution in the kernel filesystem layer for seed/default files, writable files, app syscalls, LARDX, LDLL, and Y:/Z:/A: MediaFS stores.
ITEM Keeps RXR alias priority for rxr/name so app-bundle dependency files remain install-path independent.
ITEM Keeps quoted path words plus vpath/pathmap so users can inspect and control the visible mapping before using it.
ITEM Ships the full hardware-profiled IMG/ISO set for universal, seabios, ami, vbox, usb, and realpc.

SECTION v1.76.0b
ITEM Beta release generalizing OS virtual file paths beyond RXR bundles.
ITEM Any path shaped folder/inside/path is resolved by the kernel filesystem layer to a safe flat LardOS filename, and MediaFS applies the same rule for Y:/Z:/A: device stores.
ITEM RXR aliases still take priority for rxr/name, preserving app-bundle dependency behavior while moving the general rule into FS.
ITEM LSH now accepts quoted path words for paths with spaces and adds vpath/pathmap so users can inspect the visible mapping before opening, writing, copying, or renaming.
ITEM POST and LUNIT now cover the generic virtual path namespace while preserving RXR/RXE/SYSRXE, KMO, DRFL, MediaFS, WebStack, and user-owned control behavior without feature loss.

SECTION v1.75.1b
ITEM Beta release correcting RXR paths to be OS-centered instead of app-runtime centered.
ITEM The kernel filesystem layer now resolves rxr/name before read-only open, writable open, writable create, capacity checks, and rename operations.
ITEM LSH and apps no longer need a special path rewrite to use bundle dependency files; they pass rxr/name to the OS namespace and FS owns the mapping.
ITEM POST now checks both the RXR path parser and fs_open("rxr/notes.txt") so the namespace behavior is tested where it belongs.
ITEM Preserves RXR/RXE/SYSRXE app bundles, user-owned file editing, undo behavior, KMO, DRFL, MediaFS, WebStack, and the no-hidden-control value rule.

SECTION v1.75.0b
ITEM Beta release adding RXR bundle-internal paths for RXE/SYSRXE apps and their dependency files.
ITEM Apps installed from .rxr can open rxr/name through LSH commands, C-style app code that calls lsh("..."), user-mode SYS_OPEN, LARDX loading, and LDLL loading.
ITEM Added rxr path rxr/file plus rxr aliases/map so users can inspect the visible alias from bundle path to installed file target.
ITEM Updated sample.rxr so the demo app reads rxr/rxr_data.txt instead of hard-coding the installed dependency name.
ITEM POST now checks the RXR path resolver, preserving RXR/RXE/SYSRXE, KMO, DRFL, MediaFS, WebStack, and user-owned control behavior without feature loss.

SECTION v1.74.1p
ITEM Hotpatch rollback removing the site-specific video-view beta surface from the current branch and boot media.
ITEM Removed the service-specific parser module, shell aliases, built-in guide/demo documents, POST/LUNIT checks, OSLink allowlist entry, and GUI Doc-tab special case.
ITEM The web stack returns to generic LARS link/fetch records and HTTP/HTTPS GET, POST, and HEAD handling without hard-coded third-party platform logic.
ITEM Preserves WebStack v1.73.0b, KMO, DRFL, RXR/RXE/SYSRXE, OSLink, MediaFS, GUI, and user-owned control paths without feature loss outside the withdrawn beta surface.
ITEM This release keeps the LardOS value rule: the OS should expose general user-controlled primitives, not embed a named outside service as a privileged built-in.

SECTION v1.73.0b
ITEM Beta release expanding the native web stack without switching to HTML, Markdown, or an external browser/library.
ITEM HTTP/HTTPS request construction now supports HEAD beside GET and POST; cfgsh http 1|2|3 selects GET, POST, or HEAD.
ITEM NetWatch and LardTrace now record HEAD as its own readable HTTP/HTTPS method event.
ITEM LARS documents now support link and fetch records in addition to button and input records, and larsform/larsact expose those actions.
ITEM Added webstack status, webstack guide, webstack demo, webstack_guide.lardd, and webdemo.lars so users can inspect the web layer from inside LardOS.
ITEM Added POST and LUNIT coverage for the request builder, LARS web demo, and embedded webstack guide while preserving KMO, DRFL, RXR/RXE/SYSRXE, OSLink, and user-owned control paths.

SECTION v1.72.0a
ITEM Official release promoting KMO shell-command bindings from v1.72.0b without feature loss or philosophy changes.
ITEM Keeps COMMAND, SHELL, and BIND fields in .kmo files so users can expose module files as direct shell command names.
ITEM Keeps kmo command file.kmo shell-command target default-message for creating command surfaces from writable KMO files.
ITEM Keeps normal command KMO routing through KModTalk and explicit RAW 1 / TARGET raw for user-chosen risky LSH/raw-control execution.
ITEM Keeps guistat, rawdemo, and userkmo sample command-bound modules, existing kmo run/create/raw/set/delete behavior, DRFL 2 driver-code files, RXR/RXE/SYSRXE, OSLink, hardware-profiled IMG/ISO artifacts, and the user-owned control philosophy.

SECTION v1.72.0b
ITEM Beta release making KMO files able to define shell commands without adding a new hard-coded LSH branch.
ITEM .kmo files now accept COMMAND, SHELL, or BIND to expose a module as a direct shell command name.
ITEM Added kmo command file.kmo shell-command target default-message so users can create new command surfaces from writable KMO files.
ITEM Normal KMO commands route through KModTalk targets; RAW 1 or TARGET raw still gives explicit user-owned raw-control execution when the user chooses it.
ITEM Built-in gui_status.kmo, raw_control.kmo, and writable user0.kmo now demonstrate command-bound modules through guistat, rawdemo, and userkmo.
ITEM Preserves existing kmo run/create/raw/set/delete behavior, DRFL 2 driver-code files, RXR/RXE/SYSRXE, KModTalk, OSLink, hardware-profiled IMG/ISO artifacts, and the user-owned control philosophy.

SECTION v1.71.2a
ITEM Official release promoting the driver-catalog track without feature loss or philosophy changes.
ITEM DRFL 2 makes .drfl a driver-code file: it names hardware, declares the driver type, and carries editable CODE lines as the driver source/control body.
ITEM The kernel keeps DRFL 1 binary compatibility for older metadata files, but new DRFL 2 files must carry CODE so driver behavior is visible and user-owned.
ITEM Added drivers show index|name so users can inspect loaded DRFL code, format, language, code length, and source hash from inside LardOS.
ITEM The drivers branch now ships RTL8139 and PIIX3 IDE DRFL 2 files plus RXR bundles, so installable drivers live outside the monolithic OS tree until the user chooses them.
ITEM Preserves MediaFS/MDFS drive letters from v1.71.1p, RXR, RXE/SYSRXE, KMO raw-control, KModTalk, OSLink, hardware-profiled IMG/ISO artifacts, and the user-owned control philosophy.

SECTION v1.71.1p
ITEM Hotpatch correcting the MediaFS drive-letter policy to match the LardOS memory rule: X: is main, Y:/F: is floppy, Z:/S: is auxiliary SSD/HDD, A:/U: is the first extra USB-style drive, and R: is writable RAM.
ITEM Moves RAM-file workflows from Z: to R: so Z: can stay the user-rememberable auxiliary drive without losing writable RAM files.
ITEM Keeps S:, U:, and F: as visible compatibility aliases so v1.71.0b users do not lose access to existing MediaFS commands.
ITEM Updates LSH, L-DOS, POST, built-in LARS/LARDD guides, and architecture docs so help text and diagnostics all report the same drive policy.
ITEM Preserves MediaFS/MDFS, RXR, RXE/SYSRXE, KMO raw-control, OSLink, LPST, HDD/SSD installer, hardware-profiled IMG/ISO artifacts, and the user-owned control philosophy without feature loss.

SECTION v1.71.0b
ITEM Beta release adding native media file stores for SSD/HDD, USB-style, and floppy-style device access.
ITEM Added MediaFS/MDFS plus S:, U:, and Y:/F: drives so DIR, TYPE, WRITE, APPEND, COPY, LARS/LARDD, RXR/LPACK, and DOS-mode file commands can open or save files on device stores.
ITEM MDFS uses visible in-tree records and syncs to ATA sectors after the boot image/LPST when backing storage is large enough; boot-floppy-sized images report RAM fallback honestly instead of pretending persistence.
ITEM Added media/mediafs/devstore commands: list, format, sync, read, write, append, and delete.
ITEM Preserves RXR, RXE/SYSRXE, KMO raw-control, OSLink, LPST, HDD/SSD installer, hardware-profiled IMG/ISO artifacts, and the user-owned control philosophy without feature loss.

SECTION v1.70.0a
ITEM Official release adding RXR app bundle files without feature loss or philosophy changes.
ITEM RXR 1 bundles an RXE/SYSRXE app and its required files through APP, FILE, ENDFILE, and END records.
ITEM Added rxr info/list/verify/install/undo/test plus sample.rxr and rxr_guide.lardd.
ITEM RXR install can create user-owned writable targets from RXR slots, then reload RXE/SYSRXE apps so installed apps appear without hard-coded desktop branches.
ITEM Keeps app-side LANG/CODE, APPKIT, RXE/SYSRXE split, KMO, KModTalk, OSLink, hardware-profiled IMG/ISO artifacts, raw IMG, HDD/SSD installer, and user-owned control values intact.

SECTION v1.69.0a
ITEM Official release adding app-side language runners for RXE/SYSRXE without feature loss or philosophy changes.
ITEM App files can select LANG LSH, LIL, GASM, BOSL, LAFILLO, OSVM, C, or LML and carry their own CODE lines inside the .rxe/.sysrxe file.
ITEM LANG C uses an in-kernel C-style app runner with int variables, expressions, print/println, appkit("UI ..."), lsh("command"), return, and input as a user-provided numeric value.
ITEM Added langdemo.rxe as a normal RXE file-defined app proving app code is loaded from the file rather than hard-coded into the desktop.
ITEM Keeps APPKIT file-defined/runtime UI, RXE/SYSRXE split, KMO, KModTalk, OSLink, hardware-profiled IMG/ISO artifacts, raw IMG, HDD/SSD installer, and user-owned control values intact.

SECTION v1.68.0a
ITEM Official release adding APPKIT file-defined and runtime app UI without feature loss or philosophy changes.
ITEM RXE/SYSRXE apps can declare APPKIT widgets in files and create UI at runtime with APPKIT UI, APPKIT CLEAR, APPKIT COLOR, and APPKIT LAYOUT/SURFACE output lines.
ITEM Unknown widget names become user-owned custom widgets, preserving extensibility instead of forcing hard-coded OS app branches.
ITEM GUI text now preserves unknown Unicode as grayscale barcode fallback cells that encode codepoint nibbles instead of replacing text with question marks.
ITEM The default Unicode mouse cursor and fallback cursor are tail-less, while U+E004 remains user-editable through glyph/cursor tools.
ITEM Preserves RXE/SYSRXE, KMO, KModTalk, OSLink, hardware-profiled IMG/ISO artifacts, raw IMG, HDD/SSD installer, and user-owned control values.

SECTION v1.67.2a
ITEM Official release promoting the VirtualBox optical-drive boot hotpatch from v1.67.2p without feature loss or philosophy changes.
ITEM Keeps the ISO-specific stage1 handoff, CHS-only El Torito fallback, register-safe stage2 progress output, and low-memory LARDX/BOSX staging path.
ITEM Keeps raw IMG, HDD/SSD installer, hybrid USB, hardware-profiled IMG/ISO artifacts, RXE/SYSRXE, KMO, KModTalk, OSLink, and default GUI behavior intact.
ITEM Preserves the LardOS value that the system stays user-owned, visible, native, and recoverable.

SECTION v1.67.2p
ITEM Hotpatch fixing the VirtualBox optical-drive boot failure that showed Disk read error before the GUI.
ITEM ISO boot now uses an El Torito-specific stage1 handoff and CHS-only stage2 reads for floppy-emulation media, avoiding VirtualBox CD/floppy EDD LBA mismatch.
ITEM Stage2 now preserves BIOS progress-output registers, preventing the dot printer from corrupting the kernel load offset and leaving later kernel sectors zeroed.
ITEM Stage2 keeps the LARDX/BOSX load below VGA/EBDA, enters protected mode, and then preserves the full boot-image copy at 0x01000000 for the installer.
ITEM Raw HDD/SSD and hybrid USB paths still use the existing disk-first flow, preserving installer and USB behavior.
ITEM Keeps the RXE/SYSRXE split, KMO, KModTalk, OSLink, default GUI, hardware-profiled IMG/ISO artifacts, and user-owned control values intact.

SECTION v1.67.1a
ITEM Official release promoting the corrected RXE/SYSRXE split from v1.67.1p without feature loss or philosophy changes.
ITEM Keeps SYSRXE as the system executable surface: .sysrxe files plus sysrxe list/reload/load/show/run/test.
ITEM Keeps RXE as the normal executable surface: .rxe files plus rxe list/reload/load/show/run/test, rxe_guide.lardd, GUI/dock integration, and Magic recognition.
ITEM Keeps demo_game.rxe as the native file-defined RXE maze with arrow-key GUI movement, shell movement through rxe run 0 right, reset support, and TYPE GAME board declarations.
ITEM Preserves KMO, KModTalk, OSLink, default GUI, hardware-profiled IMG/ISO artifacts, and the LardOS value that executable formats stay native and user-owned.

SECTION v1.67.1p
ITEM Hotpatch correcting the RXE naming model after v1.67.0b.
ITEM SYSRXE is now documented and exposed as the system executable surface: .sysrxe files plus the sysrxe command.
ITEM Added the normal RXE executable surface: .rxe files, rxe list/reload/load/show/run/test, rxe_guide.lardd, GUI/dock integration, and Magic command recognition.
ITEM Moved the demo maze to demo_game.rxe so the demo game is a normal RXE executable, not a SYSRXE system executable.
ITEM Removed the rxe alias from sysrxe and from KModTalk's sysrxe module alias, preserving the user's requested split without feature loss.

SECTION v1.67.0b
ITEM Beta release that introduced the first native RXE game runtime experiment.
ITEM Added TYPE GAME, GAME, BOARD, PLAYER/START, GOAL, and ROW map declarations to prove file-defined games could work.
ITEM The follow-up v1.67.1p corrected the naming split: SYSRXE is for system executables, normal games use RXE and .rxe.
ITEM Kept the game on the shared file-defined app path, so it was not a one-off hand-coded GUI branch.
ITEM Added parser selftests, POST/LUNIT file coverage, docs, and hardware-profile release support while preserving KMO, KModTalk, OSLink, and user-control values.

SECTION v1.66.1a
ITEM Official release promoting KMO raw-control from v1.66.1b without feature loss or philosophy changes.
ITEM Keeps .kmo file modules, KModTalk routing, RAW 1 / TARGET raw explicit dangerous execution, kmo raw, kmo set raw 1, and raw_control.kmo.
ITEM Keeps visible mode reporting in kmo list/show, POST and LUNIT coverage, hardware-profiled IMG/ISO artifacts, and user-owned KMO create/set/delete behavior.
ITEM Preserves the LardOS value that the user may choose the risky path when they explicitly ask for it.

SECTION v1.66.1b
ITEM Beta update adding explicit KMO raw-control mode for the user-chosen dangerous path.
ITEM Added RAW 1, DANGER 1, UNSAFE 1, MODE raw, CONTROL raw, and TARGET raw parsing in .kmo files.
ITEM Added kmo raw file.kmo command and kmo set file.kmo raw 1 so users can create or convert a KMO into direct LSH/raw-control execution.
ITEM Added raw_control.kmo as a visible sample with a safe default command that users can edit into SUM, peek, poke, asm_, power, installer, or other risky commands if they choose.
ITEM kmo show and kmo list now expose whether a module uses kmodtalk mode or raw-control mode.
ITEM Preserves KMO delete/set ownership, KModTalk logging for normal KMO, SYSRXE, OSLink, and the LardOS value that the user can choose power even when dangerous.

SECTION v1.66.0b
ITEM Beta release adding KMO, the native .kmo file format for file-stored kernel modules.
ITEM Added kmo list, kmo reload, kmo show, kmo run, kmo create, kmo set, kmo delete, and kmo test commands.
ITEM Added gui_status.kmo as a built-in sample plus writable user0.kmo through user3.kmo slots for user-created modules.
ITEM KMO files route through KModTalk targets, keeping module control visible, logged, and user-owned instead of hiding it in app-specific branches.
ITEM kmo set can take ownership of a read-only built-in KMO by hiding the original and writing a user-owned replacement; kmo delete removes KMO files from the active registry.
ITEM Added kmo_guide.lardd, POST coverage, LUNIT checks, and user-law wording without removing SYSRXE, KModTalk, OSLink, or default GUI behavior.

SECTION v1.65.1p
ITEM Hotpatch fixing rename paths for writable files, GUI app labels, and GUI folder labels.
ITEM Added native fs_rename_writable so ren and rename change the actual writable file name instead of only copying data.
ITEM Added desktop Rename action plus rename selected/app/folder shell paths for visible user-owned app and folder labels.
ITEM Added POST and LUNIT coverage for rename behavior while preserving KModTalk, SYSRXE, OSLink, and the user-control values.

SECTION v1.65.0a
ITEM Official release promoting KModTalk from v1.65.0b without feature loss or philosophy changes.
ITEM Keeps kmod and kmodtalk commands, direct handlers for gui/fs/task/oslink/boot/time/vm/sysrxe/lardkit, and writable kmodtalk.lardd history.
ITEM Keeps POST and LUNIT coverage for the direct module channel and ships hardware-profiled IMG/ISO media.
ITEM Preserves the LardOS values: user-owned control, visible logs, native C implementation, native LARDD docs, and no hidden module control path.

SECTION v1.65.0b
ITEM Beta release adding KModTalk, a direct user-to-kernel-module message surface.
ITEM Added kmod and kmodtalk commands: kmod list, kmod module message, kmod ask module message, and kmod history.
ITEM Added direct handlers for gui, fs, task, oslink, boot, time, vm, sysrxe, and lardkit kernel modules.
ITEM Module replies are shown immediately and every message is logged to writable kmodtalk.lardd for user-visible audit history.
ITEM Added kmodtalk_guide.lardd, POST coverage, LUNIT checks, and user-law wording for visible direct module communication.
ITEM Preserves SYSRXE file-defined apps, OSLink module bus paths, default GUI desktop/window direction, and user-owned control values.

SECTION v1.64.0b
ITEM Beta release adding SYSRXE, the System RXE app-file format for LardOS GUI apps.
ITEM GUI app slots now keep the existing 10 legacy apps and reserve SYSRXE slots after them, so new simple apps can be loaded from .sysrxe files instead of adding a hand-written gui.c branch each time.
ITEM Added hello.sysrxe as a built-in demo app and user-editable userapp.sysrxe as a writable starter app.
ITEM Added sysrxe list, sysrxe reload, sysrxe load, sysrxe show, sysrxe run, and sysrxe test commands in LSH.
ITEM Added sysrxe_guide.lardd, LUNIT checks, POST checks, GUI launcher integration, and overlay titles/hints for SYSRXE apps.
ITEM Preserves the separated default GUI, dock/desktop drag/delete behavior, no-EXGUI/no-EXEXGUI direction, and the user-owned native-format LardOS values.

SECTION v1.63.3p
ITEM Hotpatch for the default GUI window separation issue reported after v1.63.2p.
ITEM Removed the shared 10-tab main-GUI strip from app windows, so opening an app no longer looks like another copy of the same main window.
ITEM Each app window now shows its own app title in the title bar and app badge; switching apps is done through the desktop/dock/window stack instead of an internal main-window tab bar.
ITEM Moved app content upward to fill the space that used to be occupied by the tab strip, keeping input fields, buttons, response panes, scrollbars, and settings controls aligned.
ITEM Updated GUIOverlay so it no longer redraws the removed tab strip over the separated app windows.
ITEM Keeps v1.63.2p click/drag/delete fixes, v1.63.1p VirtualBox boot layout, and the no-EXGUI/no-EXEXGUI default GUI direction intact.

SECTION v1.63.2p
ITEM Hotpatch for default GUI desktop interaction regressions after the installer and VM boot fixes.
ITEM Desktop and dock items now keep an explicit selected state, so left-click feedback is visible and Delete knows what the user chose.
ITEM Dragging a desktop app or folder onto the dock moves it into the dock model; dragging a dock entry out onto the desktop creates a desktop launcher copy.
ITEM Dragging an item onto the Delete top-bar action deletes that desktop or dock entry, and the Delete button removes the selected entry.
ITEM Added DelFile in the desktop top bar: it uses the current local input path to clear writable RAM files or hard-delete read-only built-in/LFS files through the existing user-owned delete path.
ITEM POST now checks the desktop interaction model so click/drag/delete regressions are caught with screen diagnostics.
ITEM Keeps v1.63.1p VirtualBox boot layout, v1.63.0a installer, DEL -F ownership policy, and the no-EXGUI/no-EXEXGUI default GUI direction intact.

SECTION v1.63.1p
ITEM Hotpatch for VirtualBox black-screen boot regression after the HDD/SSD installer release.
ITEM Stage2 now stages the kernel at 0x9000 so the loaded boot image stays below the VGA/EBDA boundary on current builds.
ITEM Bootinfo moved to 0x5000 so VBE framebuffer details are not overwritten by the kernel staging buffer.
ITEM Stage2 preserves a full boot-image copy at 0x01000000 before page tables and stacks reuse low memory, so the in-OS HDD/SSD installer keeps a clean source image.
ITEM Keeps v1.63.0a install status, install hdd yes, install ssd yes, power-on I, Magic raw-control policy, and LPST LBA 2752 layout intact.
ITEM Built as hardware-profiled IMG/ISO artifacts for universal, seabios, ami, vbox, usb, and realpc.

SECTION v1.63.0a
ITEM Official release adding an in-OS HDD/SSD installer option.
ITEM The power-on options screen now accepts I for the HDD/SSD Installer, shows the target layout, and requires Y before writing.
ITEM LSH adds install status, install preview, install hdd yes, install ssd yes, and install guide.
ITEM The installer embeds the in-tree stage1/stage2 boot code, copies the current loaded LARDX/BOSX kernel image from memory, and writes LBA0, LBA1..4, and LBA5.. without external install tooling.
ITEM LPST remains reserved at LBA 2752 so installed systems keep the native writable store layout.
ITEM Magic treats install/installer as raw-control commands, so mistaken auto-execution still requires magic -f while direct user commands remain fully allowed.
ITEM Adds installer guide documentation plus POST and LUNIT coverage for the boot-stage selftest and command visibility.
ITEM Built as hardware-profiled IMG/ISO artifacts for universal, seabios, ami, vbox, usb, and realpc.

SECTION v1.62.0a
ITEM Official release making DEL -F a hard delete from the active seed/default filesystem view, not just a reversible tombstone.
ITEM DEL -F file now writes a DELETE record into fsdelete.lardd, removes the file from DIR, TYPE, and normal opens, and RESTORE/UNDELETE will not soft-restore it.
ITEM TOMB HIDE file preserves the older reversible soft tombstone path for users who want hiding instead of destruction.
ITEM TOMB LIST and TOMB SHOW distinguish soft HIDE records from hard DELETE records, while TOMB DROP file, DEL -T file, and TOMB CLEAR let the user delete those records too.
ITEM This intentionally allows the user to break the active OS file view, because LardOS policy says the machine belongs to the user.
ITEM Built as hardware-profiled IMG/ISO artifacts for universal, seabios, ami, vbox, usb, and realpc.

SECTION v1.61.0a
ITEM Official release extending L-DOS tombstone ownership to the tombstone records themselves.
ITEM Adds TOMB LIST, TOMB SHOW, TOMB DROP file, TOMB CLEAR, and DEL -T file so users can inspect, delete, or clear fsdelete.lardd tombstones without external tools.
ITEM DEL -F still hides read-only built-in or LFS files through user-owned fsdelete.lardd, while RESTORE and UNDELETE remain available for reversible visibility.
ITEM TOMB rewrites fsdelete.lardd to the user's chosen state, keeping LardOS aligned with the rule that user-visible system policy files are also user-editable.
ITEM Preserves v1.60.0a L-DOS mode, v1.60.1p read-only force-delete semantics, default GUI direction, SUM/raw-control policy, and no-feature-loss values.
ITEM Built as hardware-profiled IMG/ISO artifacts for universal, seabios, ami, vbox, usb, and realpc.

SECTION v1.60.1p
ITEM Hotpatch for L-DOS user-control deletion semantics.
ITEM DEL still clears writable RAM file contents by default, but DEL -F file now hides read-only built-in or LFS files through a user-owned fsdelete.lardd tombstone overlay.
ITEM RESTORE file and UNDELETE file remove the tombstone so forced deletions stay reversible.
ITEM DIR, TYPE, and normal file opens skip tombstoned seed/default files, while the HIDE and SHOW records remain visible in fsdelete.lardd and persist through sync.
ITEM Adds POST and LUNIT coverage for fsdelete.lardd and preserves the native C/LSH/LARDD-only DOS mode direction.

SECTION v1.60.0a
ITEM Official release adding L-DOS mode, a LardOS-native DOS-style compatibility shell layer.
ITEM Adds dos on, dos off, dos status, dos help, dos map, dos log, dos test, and dos run command.
ITEM In DOS mode the prompt becomes L-DOS C:\>, commands are case-insensitive, and familiar DIR, TYPE, COPY, DEL, REN, MD, RD, CD, CLS, VER, SET, ECHO, MEM, and EXIT commands map visibly onto LSH behavior.
ITEM Adds transparent drive mapping: C: maps to LardOS X:, A: maps to Y:, and R: maps to Z: writable RAM files.
ITEM Adds dosmode_guide.lardd, writable dosmode.lardd history, LUNIT coverage, and POST coverage for the alias parser.
ITEM Preserves the default GUI/window-manager path, EXGUI/EXEXGUI removal, user-owned Unicode cursor, SUM/raw-control policy, and no-feature-loss LardOS values.

SECTION v1.59.0a
ITEM Official release promoting the default GUI desktop/window-manager model from v1.59.0b.
ITEM Keeps runtime desktop and dock item tables, left-click launching, draggable desktop icons, reorderable dock icons, and New Folder, Pin App, and Dock + controls.
ITEM Keeps per-app window records with visibility, geometry, fullscreen state, saved view text, and z-order so covered windows render behind the active window and can be brought forward.
ITEM Preserves v1.58.1p settings/fullscreen fixes, LGUILIB/LTHEME, user-owned Unicode cursor, and the no-EXGUI/no-EXEXGUI default GUI direction.
ITEM Built as hardware-profiled IMG/ISO artifacts for universal, seabios, ami, vbox, usb, and realpc.

SECTION v1.59.0b
ITEM Beta release turning the default GUI desktop from a fixed launcher screen into a small real desktop/window-manager model.
ITEM Desktop icons and dock entries are now runtime item tables, not only hardcoded launcher arrays.
ITEM Left-click launches desktop and dock items; dragging desktop icons moves them, and dragging dock icons reorders the dock.
ITEM Added top-bar controls for New Folder, Pin App, and Dock + so users can add folders and new launchers without editing C tables.
ITEM Apps now have per-app window records with visibility, geometry, fullscreen state, saved view text, and z-order so clicking a window brings it forward and covered windows render behind it.
ITEM This is beta because it changes GUI state ownership and render ordering while preserving v1.58.1p controls, LGUILIB/LTHEME, user-owned cursor, and EXGUI/EXEXGUI removal.

SECTION v1.58.1p
ITEM Hotpatch for the latest default desktop GUI.
ITEM Settings sliders for brightness, volume, and quality now capture mouse input so clicks no longer pass through to the tab bar and close the settings panel.
ITEM Window dragging is no longer blocked by the bottom dock; normal windows can move across the full visible desktop while staying on-screen.
ITEM Added a title-bar fullscreen/restore button beside minimize and close so the default GUI can enter and leave fullscreen without EXGUI/EXEXGUI.
ITEM Keeps v1.58.0a's desktop icons, dock, LGUILIB/LTHEME path, user-owned cursor, and no-feature-loss GUI direction intact.
ITEM Built as hardware-profiled IMG/ISO artifacts for universal, seabios, ami, vbox, usb, and realpc.

SECTION v1.58.0a
ITEM Official release promoting the default GUI into a traditional desktop shell.
ITEM The default GUI now draws a persistent desktop background, top bar, desktop app icons, and a bottom dock without EXGUI or EXEXGUI.
ITEM Users can launch apps from the desktop or dock, minimize/close the app window, and reopen it from the dock instead of being stuck with one permanent window.
ITEM Keeps LGUILIB, LTHEME, glyph cursor, ScreenRAM, BugEye, Lard Buddy, LARS/LARDD apps, and all user-control features intact.
ITEM Built as hardware-profiled IMG/ISO artifacts for universal, seabios, ami, vbox, usb, and realpc.

SECTION v1.57.0b
ITEM Beta release preparing the large default GUI update by removing the optional EXGUI and EXEXGUI modules.
ITEM The default GUI is now the single GUI surface; LGUILIB, LTHEME, glyph cursor, ScreenRAM, BugEye, and Lard Buddy remain intact.
ITEM Removed exgui and exexgui commands from LSH, Magic safe-command prediction, cfgsh, POST checks, rollback snapshots, and cfg profiles.
ITEM Removed exgui.c/exexgui.c and their headers from the kernel build so future GUI polish happens in the core GUI path.
ITEM This is beta because it intentionally removes old opt-in GUI layers while preserving the rest of LardOS behavior.

SECTION v1.56.0a
ITEM Official release adding byebye as a friendlier explicit alias for bye.
ITEM byebye syncs writable RAM files, records trace and journal intent, then requests the same firmware or VM poweroff path as bye.
ITEM Magic treats byebye as raw-control; plain magic refuses it, while magic -f byebye is explicit.
ITEM Keeps v1.55.0a restart/reboot behavior, v1.54.0a magic -f behavior, and v1.53.0a bye poweroff behavior intact.
ITEM Built as hardware-profiled IMG/ISO artifacts for universal, seabios, ami, vbox, usb, and realpc.

SECTION v1.55.0a
ITEM Official release adding restart and reboot as explicit user-owned restart commands.
ITEM restart and reboot sync writable RAM files, record trace and journal intent, then request a firmware or VM restart.
ITEM Restart targets cover PCI reset control, BIOS-style 8042 reset, and a triple-fault fallback when ports are ignored.
ITEM Magic treats restart and reboot as raw-control commands; plain magic refuses them, while magic -f restart is explicit.
ITEM Keeps v1.54.0a magic -f behavior and v1.53.0a bye poweroff behavior intact.
ITEM Built as hardware-profiled IMG/ISO artifacts for universal, seabios, ami, vbox, usb, and realpc.

SECTION v1.54.0a
ITEM Official release adding magic -f as an explicit user override for raw-control Magic predictions.
ITEM Plain magic still refuses raw-control commands such as bye, byebye, poweroff, shutdown, restart, reboot, SUM, peek, poke, and asm_.
ITEM magic -f command records a force raw-control audit reason in magic explain before running the predicted command.
ITEM magic dryrun -f command previews the forced prediction without executing it.
ITEM Keeps v1.53.0a bye poweroff behavior and v1.52.6p quiet disabled scrollbar behavior intact.
ITEM Built as hardware-profiled IMG/ISO artifacts for universal, seabios, ami, vbox, usb, and realpc.

SECTION v1.53.0a
ITEM Official release adding the bye command as an explicit user-owned poweroff path.
ITEM bye syncs writable RAM files first, records trace and journal intent, then tries native VM/firmware poweroff ports.
ITEM Poweroff targets cover QEMU/ACPI, Bochs/QEMU debug poweroff, and VirtualBox; unsupported hardware falls back to a safe CPU halt.
ITEM poweroff and shutdown are aliases, but magic treats these as raw-control commands that must be run explicitly.
ITEM Keeps the v1.52.6p quiet disabled scrollbar rail and active proportional scrolling behavior.
ITEM Built as hardware-profiled IMG/ISO artifacts for universal, seabios, ami, vbox, usb, and realpc.

SECTION v1.52.6p
ITEM Hotpatch for scrollbar usability after trying the louder v1.52.5p always-visible disabled scrollbar.
ITEM Restores the quieter disabled rail for no-overflow output because it is easier to use and less visually noisy.
ITEM Keeps the active scrollbar behavior for long output: visible track, proportional thumb, and matching drag hit-test.
ITEM Keeps the v1.52.4p cursor edge behavior and user-owned Unicode cursor path intact.
ITEM Build, ISO structure checks, and QEMU GUI smoke tests were rerun for hotpatch readiness.

SECTION v1.52.5p
ITEM Hotpatch for scrollbar visibility after v1.52.4p.
ITEM The response pane now always draws a recognizable scrollbar: outer frame, top and bottom arrow caps, track, and thumb.
ITEM No-overflow output still shows a full disabled thumb so users can see that the scrollbar exists even when there is nothing to scroll.
ITEM Scrollable output continues to use a proportional thumb and the drag hit-test now matches the visible track between the arrow caps.
ITEM Keeps the cursor edge hotpatch and user-owned Unicode cursor path intact.
ITEM Build, ISO structure checks, and QEMU GUI smoke tests were rerun for hotpatch readiness.

SECTION v1.52.4p
ITEM Hotpatch for the remaining edge GUI issues reported after v1.52.3p.
ITEM Lets the Unicode cursor hotspot reach the bottom and right edge while the cursor art clips past the screen like a normal desktop pointer.
ITEM Moves screenram flushing before cursor drawing so screenram corner storage cannot hide the mouse cursor.
ITEM Makes disabled/no-overflow scrollbars visible with a muted rail and grip instead of disappearing into the output pane.
ITEM Refines the default U+E004 mouse glyph with a bright tip so it remains visible at the screen edge while staying user-owned and editable.
ITEM Build, ISO structure checks, and QEMU GUI smoke tests were rerun for hotpatch readiness.

SECTION v1.52.3p
ITEM Hotpatch for the remaining GUI boxed areas reported after v1.52.2p.
ITEM Aligns the GUI overlay output frame with the real response view so the accent line no longer crosses the input field.
ITEM Renders the Unicode cursor without hover-border effects, scales it larger for pointer readability, and seeds the default U+E004 mouse glyph as a stable non-live cursor.
ITEM Hides the bright scrollbar thumb when there is no scrollable overflow and keeps a quiet rail, while preserving proportional thumbs for longer output.
ITEM Keeps the user-owned cursor and picture Unicode editing path intact.
ITEM Build, ISO structure checks, and QEMU GUI smoke tests were rerun for hotpatch readiness.

SECTION v1.52.2p
ITEM Hotpatch for GUI mouse and response-scroll regressions after the v1.52.1p polish release.
ITEM Keeps the user-owned U+E004 cursor picture path but removes the doubled cursor draw so the glyph appears as one clean pointer.
ITEM Enables PS/2 IntelliMouse 4-byte packets and routes the wheel into response/output pane scrolling.
ITEM Uses one shared response-view rectangle for rendering, focus, wheel, and scrollbar hit-testing so visible controls and mouse behavior line up.
ITEM Computes scrollbar thumb length and position from visible rows versus total response lines, matching the actual scroll ratio.
ITEM Build, ISO structure checks, and QEMU screen smoke tests were rerun for hotpatch readiness.

SECTION v1.52.1p
ITEM Hotpatch for two small GUI polish regressions after the v1.52.0a official release.
ITEM Replaces the default U+E004 mouse Unicode picture with a clearer pointer-shaped cursor while keeping the slot user-owned and editable.
ITEM Moves the response/output pane below the input box using input-relative layout so URL/Cmd text, Response/LSH labels, and output lines no longer overlap.
ITEM Keeps the values/user-law official release direction unchanged and does not remove any existing feature surface.
ITEM Build, ISO structure checks, and QEMU screen smoke tests were rerun for hotpatch readiness.

SECTION v1.52.0a
ITEM Official promotion of the LardOS user-law value statement refresh without feature loss.
ITEM Keeps values and philosophy as direct shell aliases for rendering userlaw.lardd from inside LardOS.
ITEM Keeps the expanded userlaw reset text covering user ownership, visibility, local self-reliance, explainable automation, reversibility, repair over halt, user-grantable power, native formats, honest releases, and visible OSLink communication.
ITEM Keeps the control room and control command pointing users toward the values document as a first-class control surface.
ITEM Release media uses official a-channel versioning with universal, seabios, ami, vbox, usb, and realpc IMG/ISO artifacts.

SECTION v1.52.0b
ITEM Refreshes the LardOS user-law value statement so the OS restates its user-owned, visible, editable, explainable, recoverable design goals.
ITEM Adds values and philosophy shell aliases that render userlaw.lardd directly from inside LardOS.
ITEM Expands userlaw.lardd and userlaw reset with principles for local self-reliance, explainable automation, reversibility, repair over halt, honest releases, native formats, and visible OSLink communication.
ITEM The control room and control command now point users toward the values document as a first-class control surface.
ITEM This ships as beta because the value statement is a visible policy surface that should settle before official promotion.

SECTION v1.51.0b
ITEM Makes the default GUI cursor a pretty mouse picture glyph instead of a plain arrow fallback.
ITEM The mouse cursor lives in the user-owned picture Unicode range at U+E004 and is named mouse in glyphmap.lardd.
ITEM cursor mouse and cursor default restore the U+E004 mouse glyph, while cursor set U+E000 still lets the user choose another editable slot.
ITEM glyph demo now seeds U+E004 with the same mouse picture, and glyph pixel/rename/move/copy can edit it like any other user-owned Unicode picture.
ITEM Transparent pixels now stay transparent during live image-glyph rendering so shaped cursor glyphs do not grow a solid box.
ITEM This ships as beta while the new default cursor art and hardware-profile media are tested across targets.

SECTION v1.50.0b
ITEM Adds hardware release profiles as a separate axis from the a/b/p stability suffix.
ITEM RELEASE_HW=universal, seabios, ami, vbox, usb, or realpc now changes release directory, artifact names, ISO volume label, and embedded hardware profile.
ITEM make release-all-hardware builds the whole hardware profile set with IMG and ISO media for each target.
ITEM release policy, ver, and status now show the selected hardware profile inside LardOS.
ITEM This ships as beta because hardware-specific release packaging should be tested across real machines and virtual machines before promotion.

SECTION v1.49.1p
ITEM Hotpatch for real-machine and VM boot reliability after the v1.49.0a official release.
ITEM Added a hybrid ISO MBR path so the ISO can boot when written raw to USB tools such as Rufus, while keeping El Torito floppy-emulation boot.
ITEM Added an AMI-friendlier A20 fallback and disk reset path in the BIOS boot stack.
ITEM Network startup failures now continue offline instead of panicking, improving VirtualBox default-device behavior.
ITEM PS/2 mouse initialization now explicitly enables the aux clock and the default GUI cursor is an arrow instead of a square.
ITEM The idle screensaver counter is slowed to avoid immediate tight-loop activation on fast virtual machines.
ITEM Build, git diff --check, QEMU IMG boot, and QEMU ISO boot were rerun for hotpatch readiness.

SECTION v1.49.0a
ITEM Official promotion of the VM Monitor and Shrine subsystem beta track without feature loss.
ITEM Fixed shrine verify so BOSL .shrine payloads must include valid BOSL magic and supported version before they are accepted.
ITEM Fixed the Shrine/LSS selftest so POST no longer mutates user-visible LSS counters or last-file state.
ITEM Keeps vm status, vm limits, vm selftest, vm clear, and shared step budgets for BOSL, LIL, GASM, Lafillo VM, and OSVM.
ITEM Keeps shrine, lss, and srine status, list, info, verify, run, and test commands plus shrine_guide.lardd.
ITEM Build, LSS host regression, git diff --check, QEMU IMG boot, and QEMU ISO boot were rerun for official-release readiness.
ITEM Release media uses official a-channel versioning with ISO and IMG artifacts.

SECTION v1.48.0b
ITEM Expanded LSS into a visible Shrine subsystem instead of leaving only the hello.shrine sample.
ITEM Added shrine/lss/srine status, list, info, verify, run, and test commands for .shrine wrappers.
ITEM LSS now tracks initialization, runs, failures, verified files, unsupported types, last type, last size, last file, and last error.
ITEM Added shrine_guide.lardd, LardOS control-room links, LUNIT coverage, and POST coverage for hello.shrine plus the LSS wrapper selftest.
ITEM The .shrine wrapper keeps the current in-tree format: LSS\0, one-byte type, and type 0 BOSL payload; type 1 stays reserved.
ITEM Release media uses beta b-channel versioning while the Shrine compatibility surface stabilizes.

SECTION v1.47.0b
ITEM Added VM Monitor for BOSL, LIL, GASM, Lafillo VM, and OSVM.
ITEM Added vm status, vm limits, vm selftest, and vm clear for per-VM runs, failures, budget hits, last steps, max steps, and return code.
ITEM GASM and Lafillo VM now use common step budgets so runaway programs stop instead of hanging the OS surface.
ITEM BOSL JIT now falls back to the budgeted interpreter for branchy programs, keeping loops visible and interruptible.
ITEM Added gasm file.gasm to LSH and vm_guide.lardd to the in-kernel document set.
ITEM POST and LUNIT cover VM Monitor budgets, vm_guide.lardd, and the new vm/gasm command surfaces.
ITEM Release media uses beta b-channel versioning while the VM safety and monitor UI stabilize.

SECTION v1.46.0a
ITEM Official promotion of the LardOS Time beta track without feature loss.
ITEM Keeps LardOS Time ticks from 00000-01-01, five-digit year output, Dangun year, and native lunar display.
ITEM Keeps time, date, lunar, dangun, and lardtime explain shell commands plus SYS_GET_TIME/LIL/BOSL LardOS Time ticks.
ITEM Includes the boot stack, bootinfo, and long-mode stack layout fix for larger in-tree kernels.
ITEM Includes the Lafillo ASM parser forward-progress fix so boot-time language demos do not stall the GUI.
ITEM POST, LUNIT, host lardtime selftest, QEMU IMG boot, and QEMU ISO boot were rerun for official-release readiness.
ITEM Release media uses official a-channel versioning with ISO and IMG artifacts.

SECTION v1.45.0b
ITEM Added LardOS Time: ticks count from 00000-01-01 00:00:00 instead of Unix epoch seconds.
ITEM Added five-digit year output to prevent the visible Y10K bug; years 00000..10000+ print without truncation.
ITEM Added Dangun year view with CE+2333 and the time, date, lunar, and dangun shell commands.
ITEM Added a native lunar calendar estimate anchored to the 02026 lunar new year for in-OS lunar display.
ITEM SYS_GET_TIME, LIL time, and BOSL time now expose LardOS Time ticks while RTC Unix seconds remain internal compatibility input.
ITEM POST and LUNIT now cover the LardOS Time calendar layer and lardtime_guide.lardd.
ITEM Moved the stage2 boot stack, bootinfo block, and long-mode entry stack away from the kernel staging buffer so larger in-tree kernels still boot cleanly.

SECTION v1.44.0a
ITEM Official promotion of the real16 PanicRoom texture, Unicode cursor assignment, and user-editable picture Unicode slot track.
ITEM The default official build now includes cursor set U+E000 plus glyph move/copy/rename/pixel without requiring the beta channel.
ITEM POST, LUNIT, QEMU IMG boot, and QEMU ISO boot were rerun for official-release readiness.
ITEM Release media uses official a-channel versioning with ISO and IMG artifacts.

SECTION v1.43.0b
ITEM Added user-editable assigned Unicode slots: glyph move, glyph copy, glyph rename, and glyph pixel.
ITEM glyph move can reassign a picture character to another U+E000..U+E0FF codepoint while preserving the user's image state.
ITEM Cursor-bound Unicode follows glyph move, so a cursor assigned to U+E000 keeps working after the user moves that slot to another codepoint.
ITEM glyph pixel edits one stored 8x8 picture-glyph cell directly with RRGGBB or AARRGGBB color input and refreshes glyphmap.lardd.
ITEM POST now labels the image-glyph check as user-editable Unicode slot coverage.

SECTION v1.42.0b
ITEM Added Unicode cursor assignment: cursor set U+E000 makes the GUI mouse cursor render from a user-owned picture Unicode slot.
ITEM The cursor renderer reuses the live image-glyph path, so assigned slots keep their realtime hover/click styling when used as a cursor.
ITEM Empty cursor slots safely fall back to the default block cursor until the user loads or demos a picture glyph.
ITEM Added cursor status counters and POST coverage for the Unicode cursor control surface.
ITEM Release media uses beta b-channel versioning while cursor-glyph ergonomics stabilize.

SECTION v1.41.0b
ITEM Beta PanicRoom real-mode texture pass: runtime panic now enters a real16 bridge window before long64 recovery.
ITEM Added a real-mode VGA default texture with an LPR badge, hazard pattern, and REAL16 label drawn from the low-memory trampoline.
ITEM PanicRoom keeps a matching long64 fallback texture so recovery controls stay visible even if the bridge is unavailable.
ITEM Added panicroom texture and CPU mode status counters for real16 PanicRoom texture attempts.
ITEM Release media uses beta b-channel versioning while the new panic recovery visuals stabilize.

SECTION v1.40.0a
ITEM Official promotion of the GUI polish, picture Unicode, clickable live glyph, and rough-edge repair beta track.
ITEM PanicRoom now connects to the real kernel panic path once the runtime is ready: panic and panic_u64 enter the recovery screen before halt.
ITEM The panic recovery screen auto-writes paniccapsule.lardd, shows crashlog.txt, can rebuild the capsule, apply the last rollback snapshot, and drop the first queued task.
ITEM LardKit selftest now verifies PanicRoom enter, capsule generation, and exit state for official-release readiness.
ITEM Release media uses official a-channel versioning with ISO and IMG artifacts.

SECTION v1.39.0b
ITEM Rough-edge repair pass for older features that only barely worked before the image glyph polish.
ITEM Fixed directory browsing so dir X: lists read-only system/LFS files and dir Z: lists every writable RAM file instead of a stale hardcoded subset.
ITEM Made notes add and notes clear keep notes.lardd and the GUI-visible notes.txt in sync.
ITEM Improved LARSView with reload, back, and actions commands plus previous-document status.
ITEM Added POST/LUNIT coverage for the repaired writable directory and command surfaces.

SECTION v1.38.0b
ITEM Made image glyphs clickable in the GUI by recording per-frame hitboxes for rendered PUA picture characters.
ITEM Added realtime glyph rendering with live shimmer, hover outline, and click flash using the GUI tick.
ITEM Added glyph live U+E000 on/off and glyph click U+E000 commands, with live state and click counts exported to glyphmap.lardd.
ITEM Added POST coverage for clickable image glyph hitboxes while keeping the classic text renderer path intact.

SECTION v1.37.0b
ITEM Expanded TempleOS-style picture Unicode into a 256-slot user-owned PUA range, U+E000..U+E0FF.
ITEM Added glyph commands for demo patterns, BMP loading, automatic slot assignment, metadata display, insertion into writable files, and glyphmap.lardd export.
ITEM Added glyph_guide.lardd, writable glyphmap.lardd, LUNIT command coverage, and POST coverage for the image glyph registry.
